issue.body:
Hi, 

There are references to the Universal Permissive License (UPL), Version  1.0 and GNU General Public License version 2 only with Classpath exception in the following files:

Do both the licenses apply to the files?

comment.body:
I can't comment on this without a runnable reproducer that demonstrates the performance problem.

So my only advice would be to ensure that compiled code can be cached between runs, e.g. in case of multiple contexts evaluating the same sources, create the `Context`s with a shared `Engine`, `eval`ing shared `Source`s; and in case of one-off runs, consider use of Native Image.

issue.title: Pass JPA Entity Object as parameter to JavaScript Function

comment.body: JavaScript is a single-threaded language. You cannot use one instance of JavaScript `Context` from multiple threads in parallel. You should use a pool of `Context` objects (or per-thread `Context`s). Do not forget to create an instance of `Engine` and pass it to all these `Context` objects (using [Context.Builder.engine()](https://www.graalvm.org/sdk/javadoc/org/graalvm/polyglot/Context.Builder.html#engine-org.graalvm.polyglot.Engine-)). It will ensure that these contexts share important resources (like optimized code for your `Source`s).

issue.title: Pass JPA Entity Object as parameter to JavaScript Function

comment.body:
> gradeList converted to the GradeList when spring @RestController pass Student Entity Object to client side, however some setting needed however this is not matter in my question.

If I understand correctly then this is the culprit of the problem. If your framework converts the structure of your entity such that its property is called differently (`GradeList` x `gradeList`) on the server and client then you cannot expect the same validation code to work on both sides.

> But at server side GraaLVM do not convert JPA Entity Object to proper java script Object.

Java-JavaScript interoperability in `graal-js` does not care what frameworks you use. You cannot expect it to do some magic for your JPA entities. It works with plain Java instances that it is given. In your case, it is given an instance of `Student` class and this class has no field `GradeList`.

Oh yes. gradeList converted to the GradeList when spring @RestController pass Student Entity Object to client side, of curse some setting needed however this is not matter in my question.
Thing is that we have StudentValidator.js that is used in client side and we want to use it also in server side. 
In normal usage when Student Entity Object passed to client side from @RestController everything is OK, we have No Error. But at server side GraaLVM do not convert JPA Entity Object to proper java script Object. 
One Solution is to convert JPA Entity to JSON string and pass to JavaScript, However this led to the performance degradation and is not feasible.
